{"type":"message","id":"b836daae","parentId":"9276e152","timestamp":"2026-04-30T15:21:53.817Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's only one email check cron job - \"Emmy Email Check (Gma...\" - running every 1 hour. It only checks Gmail. There's no separate iCloud email check cron job.\n\nBut the 11:09 email Bobby saw was an iCloud check. So the iCloud check must be happening within the same hourly email check job - meaning the script checks BOTH Gmail and iCloud in one run. The issue is that the cron job name says \"Gmail\" but it's actually checking both.\n\nWait, but Bobby said he only got an iCloud email check at 11:09 and not a Gmail check. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\nLooking at the cron job list - there's only ONE email check job (\"Emmy Email Check (Gma...\"). \n\nIf both Gmail and iCloud are being checked every hour as part of one script, why would Bobby only see the iCloud results? The job runs every hour, so something must be preventing the Gmail results from being delivered - maybe the Gmail check is failing or returning empty, or the delivery of that part of the report is being blocked somehow.\n\nWait, let me reconsider the timeline. If the job ran at 11:09, that means it started around 11:04 and the next one would be due around 12:04. But the status shows \"in 48m\" from the current time (11:17), which would put the next run at 12:05. Let me work through the math on the interval - that doesn't quite add up either way.\n\nSo the next scheduled run is around 12:05, about 48 minutes from now. Bobby's seeing an iCloud email report at 11:09 but no Gmail report, which suggests the Gmail check might be failing silently or the results aren't being delivered. The cron job name \"Email Check (Gma...\" is misleading since it's supposed to check both accounts. I should look at the actual email check script to see what's happening.\n","thinkingSignature":"a4413d11d2cdb355371e9c25717096549a4c28eef2cac7622e3f